# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: analytical-chemistry
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] It encompasses both classical techniques (e.g. titration, gravimetric analysis) and modern instrumental approaches (e.g. spectroscopy, chromatography, mass spectrometry, electrochemical methods).
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] There is also a strong trend towards miniaturization, automation, and the development of real-time, point-of-care diagnostic sensors.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Analytical chemistry has been important since the early days of chemistry, providing methods for determining which elements and chemicals are present in the object in question.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] During this period, significant contributions to analytical chemistry included the development of systematic elemental analysis by Justus von Liebig and systematized organic analysis based on the specific reactions of functional groups.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] The first instrumental analysis was flame emissive spectrometry, developed by Robert Bunsen and Gustav Kirchhoff, who discovered rubidium (Rb) and caesium (Cs) in 1860.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Most of the major developments in analytical chemistry took place after 1900.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] During this period, instrumental analysis became progressively dominant in the field.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] In particular, many of the basic spectroscopic and spectrometric techniques were discovered in the early 20th century and refined in the late 20th century.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] The separation sciences follow a similar timeline of development and have also became increasingly transformed into high-performance instruments.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] In the 1970s many of these techniques began to be used together as hybrid techniques to achieve a complete characterization of samples.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Starting in the 1970s, analytical chemistry became progressively more inclusive of biological questions (bioanalytical chemistry), whereas it had previously been largely focused on inorganic or small organic molecules.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Lasers have been increasingly used as probes and even to initiate and influence a wide variety of reactions.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] The late 20th century also saw an expansion of the application of analytical chemistry from somewhat academic chemical questions to forensic, environmental, industrial and medical questions, such as in histology.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Modern analytical chemistry is dominated by instrumental analysis.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Many analytical chemists focus on a single type of instrument.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Academics tend to either focus on new applications and discoveries or on new methods of analysis.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] The discovery of a chemical present in blood that increases the risk of cancer would be a discovery that an analytical chemist might be involved in.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] An effort to develop a new method might involve the use of a tunable laser to increase the specificity and sensitivity of a spectrometric method.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Many methods, once developed, are kept purposely static so that data can be compared over long periods of time.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] This is particularly true in industrial quality assurance (QA), forensic, and environmental applications.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Analytical chemistry plays an increasingly important role in the pharmaceutical industry where, aside from QA, it is used in the discovery of new drug candidates and in clinical applications where understanding the interactions between the drug and the patient are critical.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] The 21st century has been defined by the digitalization of analytical chemistry.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] The handling of large datasets ("big data") from instruments like Orbitrap mass spectrometers has made advanced data analysis, including machine learning, an essential skill.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] This era also focuses strongly on sustainability, leading to the green chemistry subfield of Green Analytical Chemistry, which aims to minimize the environmental impact of chemical analyses.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Although modern analytical chemistry is dominated by sophisticated instrumentation, the roots of analytical chemistry and some of the principles used in modern instruments are from traditional techniques, many of which are still used today.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] These techniques also tend to form the backbone of most undergraduate analytical chemistry educational labs.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] There are numerous qualitative chemical tests; examples include the acid test for gold and the Kastle-Meyer test for the presence of blood.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Inorganic qualitative analysis generally refers to a systematic scheme to confirm the presence of certain aqueous ions or elements by performing a series of reactions that eliminate a range of possibilities and then confirm suspected ions with a confirming test.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Sometimes small carbon-containing ions are included in such schemes.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] With modern instrumentation, these tests are rarely used but can be useful for educational purposes and in fieldwork or other situations where access to state-of-the-art instruments is not available or expedient.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Quantitative analysis is the measurement of the quantities of particular chemical constituents present in a substance.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Quantities can be measured by mass (gravimetric analysis) or volume (volumetric analysis).
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Gravimetric analysis involves determining the amount of material present by weighing the sample before and/or after some transformation.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] A common example used in undergraduate education is the determination of the amount of water in a hydrate by heating the sample to remove the water such that the difference in weight is due to the loss of water.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Titration involves the gradual addition of a measurable reactant to an exact volume of a solution being analyzed until some equivalence point is reached.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Titration is a family of techniques used to determine the concentration of an analyte.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Titrating accurately to either the half-equivalence point or the endpoint of a titration allows the chemist to determine the amount of moles used, which can then be used to determine a concentration or composition of the titrant.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Most familiar to those who have taken chemistry during secondary education is the acid-base titration involving a color-changing pH indicator, such as phenolphthalein.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] There are many other types of titrations, including potentiometric titrations and precipitation titrations.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Chemists might also create titration curves by systematically testing the pH after every added drop in order to understand different properties of the titrant.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Spectroscopy measures the interaction of the molecules with electromagnetic radiation.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Mass spectrometry measures mass-to-charge ratio of molecules using electric and magnetic fields.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] In a mass spectrometer, a small amount of sample is ionized and converted to gaseous ions, where they are separated and analyzed according to their mass-to-charge ratios.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] There are several ionization methods: electron ionization, chemical ionization, electrospray ionization, fast atom bombardment, matrix-assisted laser desorption/ionization, and others.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Also, mass spectrometry is categorized by approaches of mass analyzers: magnetic-sector, quadrupole mass analyzer, quadrupole ion trap, time-of-flight, Fourier transform ion cyclotron resonance, and so on.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Electroanalytical methods measure the potential (volts) and/or current (amps) in an electrochemical cell containing the analyte.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] These methods can be categorized according to which aspects of the cell are controlled and which are measured.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Calorimetry and thermogravimetric analysis measure the interaction of a material and heat.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Separation processes are used to decrease the complexity of material mixtures.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Chromatography, electrophoresis and field flow fractionation are representative of this field.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Chromatography can be used to determine the presence of substances in a sample, as different components in a mixture have different tendencies to adsorb onto the stationary phase or dissolve in the mobile phase.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Thus, different components of the mixture move at different speeds.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Different components of a mixture can therefore be identified by their respective R*ƒ* values, which is the ratio between the migration distance of the substance and the migration distance of the solvent front during chromatography.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] In combination with the instrumental methods, chromatography can be used in the quantitative determination of substances.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] There are different types of chromatography that differ from the media they use to separate the analyte and the sample.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] In thin-layer chromatography, the analyte mixture moves up and separates along the coated sheet under the volatile mobile phase.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] In gas chromatography, the gas phase separates the volatile analytes.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] A common method of chromatography using liquid as a mobile phase is high-performance liquid chromatography.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Combinations of the above techniques produce a "hybrid" or "hyphenated" technique.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Several examples are in popular use today and new hybrid techniques are under development.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] For example, gas chromatography-mass spectrometry, gas chromatography-infrared spectroscopy, liquid chromatography-mass spectrometry, liquid chromatography-NMR spectroscopy, liquid chromatography-infrared spectroscopy, and capillary electrophoresis-mass spectrometry.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Hyphenated separation techniques refer to a combination of two (or more) techniques to detect and separate chemicals from solutions.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Most often the other technique is some form of chromatography.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Hyphenated techniques are widely used in chemistry and biochemistry.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] A slash is sometimes used instead of hyphen, especially if the name of one of the methods contains a hyphen itself.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] The visualization of single molecules, single cells, biological tissues, and nanomaterials is an important and attractive approach in analytical science.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Also, hybridization with other traditional analytical tools is revolutionizing analytical science.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Microscopy can be categorized into three different fields: optical microscopy, electron microscopy, and scanning probe microscopy.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Recently, this field is rapidly progressing because of the rapid development of the computer and camera industries.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Devices that integrate (multiple) laboratory functions on a single chip of only millimeters to a few square centimeters in size and that are capable of handling extremely small fluid volumes down to less than picoliters.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] The vast amount of data produced by modern analytical instruments has made computational data analysis an integral part of the field.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] The field of chemometrics uses statistical and mathematical methods to design optimal experimental procedures and to extract meaningful information from chemical data.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Error can be defined as numerical difference between observed value and true value.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] The experimental error can be divided into two types, systematic error and random error.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Systematic error results from a flaw in equipment or the design of an experiment while random error results from uncontrolled or uncontrollable variables in the experiment.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] An error of a measurement is an inverse measure of accurate measurement (i.e., smaller the error greater the accuracy of the measurement).
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] To use these values in a function, it may be useful to calculate the error of the function.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] A general method for analysis of concentration involves the creation of a calibration curve.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] This allows for the determination of the amount of a chemical in a material by comparing the results of an unknown sample to those of a series of known standards.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] If the concentration of an element or compound in a sample exceeds the detection range of the technique, it can simply be diluted in a pure solvent.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] If the amount in the sample is below an instrument's range of measurement, the method of addition can be used.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] In this method, a known quantity of the element or compound under study is added, and the difference between the concentration added and the concentration observed is the amount actually in the sample.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Sometimes an internal standard is added at a known concentration directly to an analytical sample to aid in quantitation.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] The amount of analyte present is then determined relative to the internal standard as a calibrant.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] An ideal internal standard is an isotopically enriched analyte which gives rise to the method of isotope dilution.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] The method of standard addition is used in instrumental analysis to determine the concentration of a substance (analyte) in an unknown sample by comparison to a set of samples of known concentration, similar to using a calibration curve.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Standard addition can be applied to most analytical techniques and is used instead of a calibration curve to solve the matrix effect problem.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] One of the most important components of analytical chemistry is maximizing the desired signal while minimizing the associated noise.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] The analytical figure of merit is known as the signal-to-noise ratio (S/N or SNR).
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Noise can arise from environmental factors as well as from fundamental physical processes.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Thermal noise results from the motion of charge carriers (usually electrons) in an electrical circuit generated by their thermal motion.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Thermal noise is white noise, meaning that the power spectral density is constant throughout the frequency spectrum.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] where *k*B is the Boltzmann constant, *T* is the temperature, *R* is the resistance, and $\Delta f$ is the bandwidth of the frequency f .
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Shot noise is a type of electronic noise that occurs when the finite number of particles (such as electrons in an electronic circuit or photons in an optical device) is small enough to give rise to statistical fluctuations in a signal.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Shot noise is a Poisson process, and the charge carriers that make up the current follow a Poisson distribution.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] where *e* is the elementary charge and *I* is the average current.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Flicker noise is electronic noise with a 1/*ƒ* frequency spectrum; as *f* increases, the noise decreases.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Flicker noise arises from a variety of sources, such as impurities in a conductive channel, generation, and recombination noise in a transistor due to base current, and so on.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] This noise can be avoided by modulation of the signal at a higher frequency, for example, through the use of a lock-in amplifier.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Environmental noise arises from the surroundings of the analytical instrument.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Sources of electromagnetic noise are power lines, radio and television stations, wireless devices, compact fluorescent lamps and electric motors.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Many of these noise sources are narrow bandwidth and, therefore, can be avoided.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Temperature and vibration isolation may be required for some instruments.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Noise reduction can be accomplished either in computer hardware or software.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Examples of hardware noise reduction are the use of shielded cable, analog filtering, and signal modulation.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Examples of software noise reduction are digital filtering, ensemble average, boxcar average, and correlation methods.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Analytical chemistry has applications across science and industry.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Great effort is being put into shrinking the analysis techniques to chip size.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Although few examples of such systems compete with traditional analysis techniques, potential advantages include size/portability, speed, and cost.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Micro total analysis system (μTAS) or lab-on-a-chip.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Microscale chemistry reduces the amount of chemicals used.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Many developments improve the analysis of biological systems.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Analytical chemistry has played a critical role in the understanding of basic science to a variety of practical applications, such as biomedical applications, environmental monitoring, quality control of industrial manufacturing, and forensic science.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] The recent developments in computer automation and information technologies have extended analytical chemistry into several new biological fields.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] For example, automated DNA sequencing machines were the basis for completing human genome projects, leading to the birth of genomics.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Protein identification and peptide sequencing by mass spectrometry opened a new field of proteomics.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] In addition to automating specific processes, there is effort to automate larger sections of lab testing, such as in companies like Emerald Cloud Lab and Transcriptic.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Analytical chemistry has been an indispensable area in the development of nanotechnology.
[src:analytical-chemistry/analytical-chemistry] Surface characterization instruments, electron microscopes and scanning probe microscopes enable scientists to visualize atomic structures with chemical characterizations.
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] In analytical chemistry, a **calibration curve**, also known as a **standard curve**, is a general method for determining the concentration of a substance in an unknown sample by comparing the unknown to a set of standard samples of known concentration.
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] A calibration curve is one approach to the problem of instrument calibration; other standard approaches may mix the standard into the unknown, giving an internal standard.
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] The calibration curve is a plot of how the instrumental response, the so-called analytical signal, changes with the concentration of the analyte (the substance to be measured).
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] In more general use, a calibration curve is a curve or table for a measuring instrument which measures some parameter indirectly, giving values for the desired quantity as a function of values of sensor output.
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] In other words, it is a description of the function $y=f(x)$ , where x is the sensor output, and y is the quantity to be measured.
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] For example, a calibration curve can be made for a particular pressure transducer to determine applied pressure from transducer output (a voltage).
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] Such a curve is typically used when an instrument uses a sensor whose calibration varies from one sample to another, or changes with time or use; if sensor output is consistent the instrument would be marked directly in terms of the measured unit.
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] The operator prepares a series of standards across a range of concentrations near the expected concentration of analyte in the unknown.
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] The concentrations of the standards must lie within the working range of the technique (instrumentation) they are using.
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] Analyzing each of these standards using the chosen technique will produce a series of measurements.
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] For most analyses a plot of instrument response vs. concentration will show a linear relationship.
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] The operator can measure the response of the unknown and, using the calibration curve, can *interpolate* to find the concentration of analyte.
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] The data – the concentrations of the analyte and the instrument response for each standard – can be fit to a straight line, using linear regression analysis.
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] This yields a model described by the equation *y = mx + y0*, where **y** is the instrument response, **m** represents the sensitivity, and **y0** is a constant that describes the background.
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] The analyte concentration (**x**) of unknown samples may be calculated from this equation.
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] Many different variables can be used as the analytical signal.
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] For instance, chromium (III) might be measured using a chemiluminescence method, in an instrument that contains a photomultiplier tube (PMT) as the detector.
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] The detector converts the light produced by the sample into a voltage, which increases with intensity of light.
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] The amount of light measured is the analytical signal.
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] The Bradford assay is a colorimetric assay that measures protein concentration.
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] The reagent Coomassie brilliant blue turns blue when it binds to arginine and aromatic amino acids present in proteins, thus increasing the absorbance of the sample.
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] The absorbance is measured using a spectrophotometer, at the maximum absorbance frequency (Amax) of the blue dye (which is 595 nm).
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] In this case, the greater the absorbance, the higher the protein concentration.
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] Data for known concentrations of protein are used to make the standard curve, plotting concentration on the X axis, and the assay measurement on the Y axis.
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] The same assay is then performed with samples of unknown concentration.
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] To analyze the data, one locates the measurement on the Y-axis that corresponds to the assay measurement of the unknown substance and follows a line to intersect the standard curve.
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] The corresponding value on the X-axis is the concentration of substance in the unknown sample.
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] As expected, the concentration of the unknown will have some error which can be calculated from the formula below.
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] This formula assumes that a linear relationship is observed for all the standards.
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] Most analytical techniques use a calibration curve.
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] There are a number of advantages to this approach.
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] First, the calibration curve provides a reliable way to calculate the uncertainty of the concentration calculated from the calibration curve (using the statistics of the least squares line fit to the data).
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] Second, the calibration curve provides data on an empirical relationship.
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] The mechanism for the instrument's response to the analyte may be predicted or understood according to some theoretical model, but most such models have limited value for real samples.
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] Many theoretical relationships, such as fluorescence, require the determination of an instrumental constant anyway, by analysis of one or more reference standards; a calibration curve is a convenient extension of this approach.
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] The calibration curve for a particular analyte in a particular (type of) sample provides the empirical relationship needed for those particular measurements.
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] The chief disadvantages are (1) that the standards require a supply of the analyte material, preferably of high purity and in known concentration, and (2) that the standards and the unknown are in the same matrix.
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] Some analytes – e.g., particular proteins – are extremely difficult to obtain pure in sufficient quantity.
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] Other analytes are often in complex matrices, e.g., heavy metals in pond water.
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] In this case, the matrix may interfere with or attenuate the signal of the analyte.
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] Therefore, a comparison between the standards (which contain no interfering compounds) and the unknown is not possible.
[src:analytical-chemistry/calibration-curve] The method of standard addition is a way to handle such a situation.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] The **limit of detection** (**LOD** or **LoD**) is the lowest signal, or the lowest corresponding quantity to be determined (or extracted) from the signal, that can be observed with a sufficient degree of confidence or statistical significance.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] The detection limit is estimated from the mean of the blank, the standard deviation of the blank, the slope (analytical sensitivity) of the calibration plot and a defined confidence factor (e.g.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] 3.2 being the most accepted value for this arbitrary value).
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] Another consideration that affects the detection limit is the adequacy and the accuracy of the model used to predict concentration from the raw analytical signal.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] There are a number of concepts derived from the detection limit that are commonly used.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] These include the **instrument detection limit** (**IDL**), the **method detection limit** (**MDL**), the **practical quantitation limit** (**PQL**), and the **limit of quantitation** (**LOQ**).
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] Even when the same terminology is used, there can be differences in the LOD according to nuances of what definition is used and what type of noise contributes to the measurement and calibration.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] (The identical spread along Abscissa of these two functions is problematic.) For a signal at the LOD, the alpha error (probability of false positive) is small (1%).
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] However, the beta error (probability of a false negative) is 50% for a sample that has a concentration at the LOD (red line).
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] This means a sample could contain an impurity at the LOD, but there is a 50% chance that a measurement would give a result less than the LOD.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] At the LOQ (blue line), there is minimal chance of a false negative.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] associated with blank, detection limit (LOD), and quantitation limit (LOQ) level samples.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] Most analytical instruments produce a signal even when a blank (matrix without analyte) is analyzed.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] This signal is referred to as the noise level.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] The instrument detection limit (IDL) is the analyte concentration that is required to produce a signal greater than three times the standard deviation of the noise level.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] This may be practically measured by analyzing 8 or more standards at the estimated IDL then calculating the standard deviation from the measured concentrations of those standards.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] The detection limit (according to IUPAC) is the smallest concentration, or the smallest absolute amount, of analyte that has a signal statistically significantly larger than the signal arising from the repeated measurements of a reagent blank.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] where, $S_{reag}$ is the mean value of the signal for a reagent blank measured multiple times, and $\sigma _{reag}$ is the known standard deviation for the reagent blank's signal.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] Other approaches for defining the detection limit have also been developed.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] In atomic absorption spectrometry usually the detection limit is determined for a certain element by analyzing a diluted solution of this element and recording the corresponding absorbance at a given wavelength.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] The 3σ of the recorded absorbance signal can be considered as the detection limit for the specific element under the experimental conditions: selected wavelength, type of flame or graphite oven, chemical matrix, presence of interfering substances, instrument... .
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] Often there is more to the analytical method than just performing a reaction or submitting the analyte to direct analysis.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] Many analytical methods developed in the laboratory, especially these involving the use of a delicate scientific instrument, require a sample preparation, or a pretreatment of the samples prior to being analysed.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] For example, it might be necessary to heat a sample that is to be analyzed for a particular metal with the addition of acid first (digestion process).
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] The sample may also be diluted or concentrated prior to analysis by means of a given instrument.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] Additional steps in an analysis method add additional opportunities for errors.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] Since detection limits are defined in terms of errors, this will naturally increase the measured detection limit.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] This "*global*" detection limit (including all the steps of the analysis method) is called the method detection limit (MDL).
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] The practical way for determining the MDL is to analyze seven samples of concentration near the expected limit of detection.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] The standard deviation is then determined.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] The one-sided Student's t-distribution is determined and multiplied versus the determined standard deviation.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] For seven samples (with six degrees of freedom) the t value for a 99% confidence level is 3.14.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] Rather than performing the complete analysis of seven identical samples, if the Instrument Detection Limit is known, the MDL may be estimated by multiplying the Instrument Detection Limit, or Lower Level of Detection, by the dilution prior to analyzing the sample solution with the instrument.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] This estimation, however, ignores any uncertainty that arises from performing the sample preparation and will therefore probably underestimate the true MDL.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] The issue of limit of detection, or limit of quantification, is encountered in all scientific disciplines.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] This explains the variety of definitions and the diversity of jurisdiction specific solutions developed to address preferences.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] In the simplest cases as in nuclear and chemical measurements, definitions and approaches have probably received the clearer and the simplest solutions.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] In biochemical tests and in biological experiments depending on many more intricate factors, the situation involving false positive and false negative responses is more delicate to handle.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] In many other disciplines such as geochemistry, seismology, astronomy, dendrochronology, climatology, life sciences in general, and in many other fields impossible to enumerate extensively, the problem is wider and deals with signal extraction out of a background of noise.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] It involves complex statistical analysis procedures and therefore it also depends on the models used, the hypotheses and the simplifications or approximations to be made to handle and manage uncertainties.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] When the data resolution is poor and different signals overlap, different deconvolution procedures are applied to extract parameters.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] The use of different phenomenological, mathematical and statistical models may also complicate the exact mathematical definition of limit of detection and how it is calculated.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] This explains why it is not easy to come to a general consensus, if any, about the precise mathematical definition of the expression of limit of detection.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] However, one thing is clear: it always requires a sufficient number of data (or accumulated data) and a rigorous statistical analysis to render better signification statistically.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] The limit of quantification (LoQ, or LOQ) is the lowest value of a signal (or concentration, activity, response...) that can be quantified with acceptable precision and accuracy.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] The LoQ is the limit at which the difference between two distinct signals / values can be discerned with a reasonable certainty, *i.e.*, when the signal is statistically different from the background.
[src:analytical-chemistry/detection-limit] The LoQ may be drastically different between laboratories, so another detection limit is commonly used that is referred to as the **Practical Quantification Limit** (PQL).
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] The four main types of this method of analysis are *precipitation*, *volatilization*, *electro-analytical*, and *miscellaneous physical method*.
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] The methods involve changing the phase of the analyte to separate it in its pure form from the original mixture and are quantitative measurements.
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] Gravimetric analysis provides for exceedingly precise analysis.
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] In fact, gravimetric analysis was used to determine the atomic masses of many elements in the periodic table to six figure accuracy.
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] Gravimetry provides very little room for instrument error and does not require a series of standards for calculation of an unknown.
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] Also, gravimetric methods often do not require expensive equipment.
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] Due to its high degree of accuracy, gravimetric analysis can also be used to calibrate other instruments instead of using reference standards.
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] To some extent, gravimetric analysis has been displaced by spectroscopic methods, which are faster, highly specific, and entail less intervention.
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] For example, silver ions can be quantified by precipitiation of silver chloride, but this approach is now archaic.
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] In terms of disadvantages, gravimetric analysis usually only provides for the analysis of one of a few elements.
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] Challenges to precipitations are related to impurities in the solid, which can be caused by occlusions or surface adsorption of other ions.
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] Some problems can be averted using homogeneous precipitation, which is the formation of the precipitate from a single homogeneous solution, as in the case of barium sulfate.
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] The insolubility of precipitates can be affected by other ions in the solution.
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] The solubility of silver chloride (AgCl; Ksp = 1.0 × 10−10 in 0.1 M NaNO3) can increase by many orders of magnitude in the presence of other anions.
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] Potassium (K) can be quantified using hexachloroplatinic acid as the precipitating agent.
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] A similar analytical procedure yields a precipitate of potassium tetraphenylborate from sodium tetraphenylborate.
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] Addition of aqueous solution of ammonium molybdate to a solution containing hydrogen phosphate gives a precipitate of ammonium phosphomolybdate.
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] Several applications of gravimetric analysis employ organic ligands that generate precipitates with a specific metal ion.
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] A solution of nickel ions is treated with a > 2 equivalents of dimethylglyoxime to give a bright red precipitate of nickel bis(dimethylglyoximate).
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] In a similar approach, a solution of aluminium ions is treated with 8-hydroxyquinoline to give aluminium tris(8-Hydroxyquinolinate).
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] Barium sulfate is highly insoluble in water.
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] Using homogeneous precipitation, a sample solution containing barium ions is treated with an excess of sulfamic acid.
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] The precipitate is weighed, and the difference in weights before and after reveals the mass of analyte lost, in this case calcium oxide.
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] That number can then be used to calculate the amount, or the percent concentration, of calcium oxide analyte in the original mix.
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] In volatilization methods, removal of the analyte involves separation by heating or chemically decomposing a volatile sample at a suitable temperature.
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] In other words, thermal or chemical energy is used to precipitate a volatile species.
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] For example, the water content of a compound can be determined by vaporizing the water using thermal energy (heat).
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] Heat can also be used, if oxygen is present, for combustion to isolate the suspect species and obtain the desired results.
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] The two most common gravimetric methods using volatilization are those for water and carbon dioxide.
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] An example of this method is the isolation of sodium bicarbonate (the main ingredient in most antacid tablets) from a mixture of carbonate and bicarbonate.
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] The total amount of this analyte, in whatever form, is obtained by addition of an excess of dilute sulfuric acid to the analyte in solution.
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] In this reaction, nitrogen gas is introduced through a tube into the flask which contains the solution.
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] As it passes through, it gently bubbles.
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] The gas then exits, first passing a drying agent (here CaSO4, the common desiccant *Drierite*).
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] It then passes a mixture of the drying agent *and* sodium hydroxide which lies on asbestos or *Ascarite II*, a non-fibrous silicate containing sodium hydroxide.
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] The mass of the carbon dioxide is obtained by measuring the increase in mass of this absorbent.
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] This is performed by measuring the difference in weight of the tube in which the asbestos contained before and after the procedure.
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] The calcium sulfate (CaSO4) in the tube retains carbon dioxide selectively as it's heated, and thereby, removed from the solution.
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] The drying agent absorbs any aerosolized water and/or water vapor (reaction 3).
[src:analytical-chemistry/gravimetric-analysis] The mix of the drying agent and NaOH absorbs the CO2 and any water that may have been produced as a result of the absorption of the NaOH (reaction 4).
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] The word "titration" descends from the French word *tiltre* (1543), meaning the proportion of gold or silver in coins or in works of gold or silver; i.e., a measure of fineness or purity.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] *Tiltre* became *titre*, which thus came to mean the "fineness of alloyed gold", and then the "concentration of a substance in a given sample".
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] In 1828, the French chemist Joseph Louis Gay-Lussac first used *titre* as a verb (*titrer*), meaning "to determine the concentration of a substance in a given sample".
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] Volumetric analysis originated in late 18th-century France.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] French chemist François-Antoine-Henri Descroizilles developed the first burette (which was similar to a graduated cylinder) in 1791.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] Gay-Lussac developed an improved version of the burette that included a side arm, and invented the terms "pipette" and "burette" in an 1824 paper on the standardization of indigo solutions.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] The first true burette was invented in 1845 by the French chemist Étienne-Ossian Henry (1798–1873).
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] A typical titration begins with a beaker or Erlenmeyer flask containing a very precise amount of the analyte and a small amount of indicator (such as phenolphthalein) placed underneath a calibrated burette or chemistry pipetting syringe containing the titrant.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] Depending on the endpoint desired, single drops or less than a single drop of the titrant can make the difference between a permanent and temporary change in the indicator.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] The beaker or flask containing the analyte/indicator solution should be continuously stirred or agitated in order to keep the added titrant uniformly dispersed.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] Typical titrations require titrant and analyte to be in a liquid (solution) form.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] Though solids are usually dissolved into an aqueous solution, other solvents such as glacial acetic acid or ethanol are used for special purposes (as in petrochemistry, which specializes in petroleum.) Concentrated analytes are often diluted to improve accuracy.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] Many non-acid–base titrations require a constant pH during the reaction.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] Therefore, a buffer solution may be added to the titration chamber to maintain the pH.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] In instances where two reactants in a sample may react with the titrant and only one is the desired analyte, a separate masking solution may be added to the reaction chamber which eliminates the effect of the unwanted ion.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] Some reduction-oxidation (redox) reactions may require heating the sample solution and titrating while the solution is still hot to increase the reaction rate.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] For instance, the oxidation of some oxalate solutions requires heating to 60 °C (140 °F) to maintain a reasonable rate of reaction.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] In an acid–base titration, the titration curve represents the strength of the corresponding acid and base.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] For a strong acid and a strong base, the curve will be relatively smooth and very steep near the equivalence point.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] Because of this, a small change in titrant volume near the equivalence point results in a large pH change, and many indicators would be appropriate (for instance litmus, phenolphthalein or bromothymol blue).
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] If one reagent is a weak acid or base and the other is a strong acid or base, the titration curve is irregular and the pH shifts less with small additions of titrant near the equivalence point.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] For example, the titration curve for the titration between oxalic acid (a weak acid) and sodium hydroxide (a strong base) is pictured.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] The equivalence point occurs between pH 8-10, indicating the solution is basic at the equivalence point and an indicator such as phenolphthalein would be appropriate.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] Titration curves corresponding to weak bases and strong acids are similarly behaved, with the solution being acidic at the equivalence point and indicators such as methyl orange and bromothymol blue being most appropriate.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] Titrations between a weak acid and a weak base have titration curves which are very irregular.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] Because of this, no definite indicator may be appropriate, and a pH meter is often used to monitor the reaction.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] The type of function that can be used to describe the curve is termed a sigmoid function.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] There are many types of titrations with different procedures and goals.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] The most common types of qualitative titration are acid–base titrations and redox titrations.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] Acid–base titrations depend on the neutralization between an acid and a base when mixed in solution.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] In addition to the sample, an appropriate pH indicator is added to the titration chamber, representing the pH range of the equivalence point.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] The acid–base indicator indicates the endpoint of the titration by changing color.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] The endpoint and the equivalence point are not exactly the same because the equivalence point is determined by the stoichiometry of the reaction while the endpoint is just the color change from the indicator.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] Thus, a careful selection of the indicator will reduce the indicator error.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] For example, if the equivalence point is at a pH of 8.4, then the phenolphthalein indicator would be used instead of Alizarin Yellow because phenolphthalein would reduce the indicator error.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] Common indicators, their colors, and the pH range in which they change color are given in the table above.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] When more precise results are required, or when the reagents are a weak acid and a weak base, a pH meter or a conductance meter are used.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] For very strong bases, such as organolithium reagent, metal amides, and hydrides, water is generally not a suitable solvent and indicators whose pKa are in the range of aqueous pH changes are of little use.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] Instead, the titrant and indicator used are much weaker acids, and anhydrous solvents such as THF are used.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] The approximate pH during titration can be approximated by three kinds of calculations.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] Before beginning of titration, the concentration of ${\ce {[H+]}}$ is calculated in an aqueous solution of weak acid before adding any base.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] When the number of moles of bases added equals the number of moles of initial acid or so called equivalence point, one of hydrolysis and the pH is calculated in the same way that the conjugate bases of the acid titrated was calculated.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] Between starting and end points, ${\ce {[H+]}}$ is obtained from the Henderson-Hasselbalch equation and titration mixture is considered as buffer.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] In Henderson-Hasselbalch equation the [acid] and [base] are said to be the molarities that would have been present even with dissociation or hydrolysis.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] In a buffer, ${\ce {[H+]}}$ can be calculated exactly but the dissociation of HA, the hydrolysis of ${\ce {A-}}$ and self-ionization of water must be taken into account.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] In the equations, $n_{{\ce {A}}}$ and $n_{{\ce {B}}}$ are the moles of acid (HA) and salt (XA where X is the cation), respectively, used in the buffer, and the volume of solution is V.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] The law of mass action is applied to the ionization of water and the dissociation of acid to derived the first and second equations.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] The mass balance is used in the third equation, where the sum of $V[{\ce {HA}}]$ and $V[{\ce {A-}}]$ must equal to the number of moles of dissolved acid and base, respectively.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] Redox titrations are based on a reduction-oxidation reaction between an oxidizing agent and a reducing agent.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] A potentiometer or a redox indicator is usually used to determine the endpoint of the titration, as when one of the constituents is the oxidizing agent potassium dichromate.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] The color change of the solution from orange to green is not definite, therefore an indicator such as sodium diphenylamine is used.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] Analysis of wines for sulfur dioxide requires iodine as an oxidizing agent.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] In this case, starch is used as an indicator; a blue starch-iodine complex is formed in the presence of excess iodine, signalling the endpoint.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] Some redox titrations do not require an indicator, due to the intense color of the constituents.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] For instance, in permanganometry a slight persisting pink color signals the endpoint of the titration because of the color of the excess oxidizing agent potassium permanganate.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] In iodometry, at sufficiently large concentrations, the disappearance of the deep red-brown triiodide ion can itself be used as an endpoint, though at lower concentrations sensitivity is improved by adding starch indicator, which forms an intensely blue complex with triiodide.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] Gas phase titrations are titrations done in the gas phase, specifically as methods for determining reactive species by reaction with an excess of some other gas, acting as the titrant.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] After the reaction is complete, the remaining titrant and product are quantified (e.g., by Fourier transform spectroscopy) (FT-IR); this is used to determine the amount of analyte in the original sample.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] Gas phase titration has several advantages over simple spectrophotometry.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] First, the measurement does not depend on path length, because the same path length is used for the measurement of both the excess titrant and the product.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] Second, the measurement does not depend on a linear change in absorbance as a function of analyte concentration as defined by the Beer–Lambert law.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] Third, it is useful for samples containing species which interfere at wavelengths typically used for the analyte.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] Complexometric titrations rely on the formation of a complex between the analyte and the titrant.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] In general, they require specialized complexometric indicators that form weak complexes with the analyte.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] The most common example is the use of starch indicator to increase the sensitivity of iodometric titration, the dark blue complex of starch with iodine and iodide being more visible than iodine alone.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] Other complexometric indicators are Eriochrome Black T for the titration of calcium and magnesium ions, and the chelating agent EDTA used to titrate metal ions in solution.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] Zeta potential titrations are titrations in which the completion is monitored by the zeta potential, rather than by an indicator, in order to characterize heterogeneous systems, such as colloids.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] One of the uses is to determine the iso-electric point when surface charge becomes zero, achieved by changing the pH or adding surfactant.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] Another use is to determine the optimum dose for flocculation or stabilization.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] An assay is a type of biological titration used to determine the concentration of a virus or bacterium.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] Serial dilutions are performed on a sample in a fixed ratio (such as 1:1, 1:2, 1:4, 1:8, etc.) until the last dilution does not give a positive test for the presence of the virus.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] The positive or negative value may be determined by inspecting the infected cells visually under a microscope or by an immunoenzymetric method such as enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay (ELISA).
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] Though the terms equivalence point and endpoint are often used interchangeably, they are different terms.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] *Equivalence point* is the theoretical completion of the reaction: the volume of added titrant at which the number of moles of titrant is equal to the number of moles of analyte, or some multiple thereof (as in polyprotic acids).
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] *Endpoint* is what is actually measured, a physical change in the solution as determined by an indicator or an instrument mentioned above.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] There is a slight difference between the endpoint and the equivalence point of the titration.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] This error is referred to as an indicator error, and it is indeterminate.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] Back titration is a titration done in reverse; instead of titrating the original sample, a known excess of standard reagent is added to the solution, and the excess is titrated.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] A back titration is useful if the endpoint of the reverse titration is easier to identify than the endpoint of the normal titration, as with precipitation reactions.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] Back titrations are also useful if the reaction between the analyte and the titrant is very slow, or when the analyte is in a non-soluble solid.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] The titration process creates solutions with compositions ranging from pure acid to pure base.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] Identifying the pH associated with any stage in the titration process is relatively simple for monoprotic acids and bases.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] The presence of more than one acid or base group complicates these computations.
[src:analytical-chemistry/titration] Graphical methods, such as the equiligraph, have long been used to account for the interaction of coupled equilibria.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] Wet chemistry commonly uses laboratory glassware such as beakers and graduated cylinders to prevent materials from being contaminated or interfered with by unintended sources.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] Gasoline, Bunsen burners, and crucibles may also be used to evaporate and isolate substances in their dry forms.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] Wet chemistry is not performed with any advanced instruments since most automatically scan substances.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] Although, simple instruments such as scales are used to measure the weight of a substance before and after a change occurs.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] Many high school and college laboratories teach students basic wet chemistry methods.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] Before the age of theoretical and computational chemistry, wet chemistry was the predominant form of scientific discovery in the chemical field.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] This is why it is sometimes referred to as **classic chemistry** or **classical chemistry**.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] Scientists would continuously develop techniques to improve the accuracy of wet chemistry.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] Later on, instruments were developed to conduct research impossible for wet chemistry.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] Over time, this became a separate branch of analytical chemistry called instrumental analysis.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] Because of the high volume of wet chemistry that must be done in today's society and new quality control requirements, many wet chemistry methods have been automated and computerized for streamlined analysis.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] The manual performance of wet chemistry mostly occurs in schools.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] Qualitative methods use changes in information that cannot be quantified to detect a change.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] This can include a change in color, smell, texture, etc.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] Chemical tests use reagents to indicate the presence of a specific chemical in an unknown solution.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] The reagents cause a unique reaction to occur based on the chemical it reacts with, allowing one to know what chemical is in the solution.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] An example is Heller's test where a test tube containing proteins has strong acids added to it.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] A cloudy ring forms where the substances meet, indicating the acids are denaturing the proteins.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] The cloud is a sign that proteins are present in a liquid.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] The method is used to detect proteins in a person's urine.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] The flame test is a more well known version of the chemical test.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] The metal powder is burned, causing an emission of colors based on what metal was burned.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] For example, calcium (Ca) will burn orange and copper (Cu) will burn blue.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] Their color emissions are used to produce bright colors in fireworks.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] Quantitative methods use information that can be measured and quantified to indicate a change.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] This can include changes in volume, concentration, weight, etc.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] Gravimetric analysis measures the weight or concentration of a solid that has either formed from a precipitate or dissolved in a liquid.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] The mass of the liquid is recorded before undergoing the reaction.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] For the precipitate, a reagent is added until the precipitate stops forming.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] The precipitate is then dried and weighed to determine the chemicals concentration in the liquid.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] For a dissolved substance, the liquid can be filtered until the solids are removed or boiled until all the liquid evaporates.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] The solids are left alone until completely dried and then weighed to determine its concentration.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] Evaporating all the liquid is the more common approach.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] Volumetric analysis or titration relies on volume measurements to determine the quantity of a chemical.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] A reagent with a known volume and concentration is added to a solution with an unknown substance or concentration.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] The amount of reagent required for a change to occur is proportional to the amount of the unknown substances.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] This reveals the amount of the unknown substance present.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] If no visible change is present, an indicator is added to the solution.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] For example, a pH indicator changes color based on the pH of the solution.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] The exact point where the color change occurs is called the endpoint.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] Since the color change can occur very suddenly, it is important to be extremely precise with all measurements.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] Colorimetry is a unique method since it has both qualitative and quantitative properties.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] Its qualitative analysis involves recording color changes to indicate a change has occurred.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] This can be a change in shading of the color or a change into a completely different color.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] The quantitative aspect involves sensory equipment that can measure the wavelength of colors.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] Changes in wavelengths can be precisely measured and indicate changes in the mixture or solution.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] Wet chemistry techniques can be used for qualitative chemical measurements, such as changes in color (colorimetry), but often involves more quantitative chemical measurements, using methods such as gravimetry and titrimetry.
[src:analytical-chemistry/wet-chemistry] Wet chemistry is also used in environmental chemistry settings to determine the current state of the environment.
